@flexiarg vsatelier/annotation-as-commitment
@title Annotation as Commitment
@audience facilitators, programme designers, cooperative learning practitioners
@tone analytic
@style design-pattern
@sigils [✍️/约]
@references [vsatlas/cooperative-learning-environment vsatlas/interpretation-offering vsatelier/decision-provenance]

! conclusion:
  Interpretive notes should be able to graduate from observations into
  commitments — named actions with owners, timelines, and completion
  criteria — so that collective sense-making produces accountable
  follow-through.

  + context: You are designing the bridge between interpretation and action within a facilitated programme. This does not apply when annotations are purely scholarly or archival.
  + IF:
    A pilot's interpretive notes surface actionable patterns —
    "these three stories describe the same unmet need" or "this
    contrast link reveals a policy gap."

  + HOWEVER:
    Notes that remain observations create a culture of noticing
    without acting. The gap between insight and response is where
    community trust erodes.

  + THEN:
    Allow any interpretive note to be promoted to a commitment:
    an action item with an owner, a deadline, a success criterion,
    and a link back to the note and its source stories. Commitments
    appear in a steward-visible tracker alongside the constellation.

  + BECAUSE:
    When annotation becomes commitment, the interpretive layer stops
    being a commentary system and becomes a planning tool. The
    constellation is no longer only a picture of the past — it is a
    surface for coordinating the future.

  + STATUS:
    status[sketch]

  + NEXT-STEPS:
    next[Extend the interpretive note schema with optional commitment fields (owner, deadline, criterion, status).]
    next[Design the steward dashboard view that shows open commitments alongside the constellation.]
    next[Test with one pilot: do promoted commitments actually get completed at a higher rate than unpromoted notes?]
